            <div type="translation">
                <p>Fastia Velsi, wife of Larza Velu.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The text labels the lid with the feminine name Fastia Velsi and identifies her as the wife of a man named Larza Velu. 
                    The initial translation published by Eldridge was erroneous, yet often republished.  A correct translation and 
                    summary of previous errors was published by Richard De Puma in 2008 and matches the translation provided by the MFA. 
                    The woman sculpted in repose on the lid may be Fastia Velsi, for whom the inscription likely indicates the urn was made.  
                    The urn with which this lid is paired may be the original, but the lack of provenance between its excavation and the sale 
                    to the MFA makes this uncertain. In either case, the size and quality of the lid indicates that the person who commissioned 
                    it and the deceased were wealthy. If the excavation information Tolentino provided to the MFA is accurate, which research 
                    by HammarstrÃ¶m in 1928 indicates it is, the urn lid dates to the third century BCE. 
                </p>
            </div>
            

